Questionnaire Survival Analysis

Questionnaire Data Set Analysis

The questionnaire section of the 2017-2020 NHANES data set has many different components, including questions on different social behaviours, health status, upbringing, medical history, environmental factors, and more. As there are almost 40 different factors explored, we decided to pick 5 that were of interest to us and/or mentioned in our literature review. The factors that we selected were: alcohol consumption, depression, access to health care, insurance status, and occupation. Alcohol is a prominent social behaviour that we thought would be interesting to explore in conjunction to diabetes as it is a integrated part of every culture. Depression appeared frequently in our literature review and we wanted to explore if there is any relationship between diabetes and depression within this data set. Access to health care and insurance status are related, and both are vital to diabetes treatment, which is why we decided to include them. Finally, we were curious about if employment status and how much someone works has any relationship with diabetes status, which is why we selected it as our final variable. The variables that weren’t selected are by no means of lesser importance to diabetes than the ones we chose. We selected only a few because we wanted to focus on a few variables in depth to get a comprehensive picture, rather than hastily exploring almost 40 variables.

Each one of the five subtopics is its own data set and has a series of individual questions within it. The alcohol data set explores general alcohol consumption behaviours, as well as quantifying how much alcohol someone consumes on average. The depression data set explores different specific feelings or states someone with depression may experience, such as difficulty sleeping, poor appetite, little will to do anything, etc. The access to health care explores how accessible health care is to the respondent including whether or not they have someone to go to receive health care regularly, and how frequently they receive health care. The insurance data set explores insurance coverage including general coverage, and what specific type of insurance an individual may have. Finally, the occupation data set explores topics such as job status, type of job, and how many hours the respondent works per week. All of these data sets have many variables and we were not able to explore all of them. Many of the variables are similar in nature and are quite specific. For example, in the alcohol data set, there are multiple questions about if the respondent has had 8+ drinks per day, and then another about whether they’ve had 6+ drinks per day. We felt that these variables didn’t provide as much information as some of the other ones, such as whether or not they’ve ever consumed alcohol or the average number of drinks per day. Therefore, for each data set, we selected a few variables that we felt summarised the topic effectively.

Diabetes & Alcohol Analysis

The variables that we selected from the alcohol data set for the alcohol and diabetes analysis were ever_had_a_drink_of_any_kind_of_alcohol and avg_alcoholic_drinks_per_day_past_12_months. As mentioned above, we felt that these two variables summarised someone’s alcohol consumption effectively. As a reminder, the event of interest in the diabetes data set is informed_of_diabetes and the time variable is age_informed.

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Ever Had Alcohol?: Yes 0.1015614 0.09466358 1.072867 0.283331

The alcohol and diabetes analysis shows us that consumption of alcohol altogether does not have a statistically significant impact on age informed of diabetes. The survival curves cross multiple times indicating that we are not able to tell if consumption of alcohol at least once in the respondent’s life has any relationship with when they are informed of their diabetes. This makes sense as “ever having a drink of alcohol” is quite a broad category. Some people in this category may only try alcohol once and never have it again, while others may drink every day. This prompted us to further explore alcohol consumption by looking at the average number of drinks per day over one year’s time span.

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Average Alcoholic Drinks Per Day Past 12 Months 0.06625601 0.01699299 3.89902 9.65827e-05

When we look at average number of drinks consumed per day over the last 12 months, we see that there is a statistically significant difference between groups of many drinks one consumes per day and a statistically significant impact on age informed of diabetes. The groups consuming 7 or more drinks a day tending to drop in survival probability earlier than groups that have fewer drinks. This implies that people who have more drinks per day are more likely to be informed of diabetes sooner and maybe implies that there is a relationship between alcohol consumption and diabetes.

It is also important to consider that this statistically significant difference could be due to the number of people in each of the drinks groups as the larger number of drinks per day group may be a smaller sample size than groups where people have fewer drinks per day, which is worth exploring. We saw in the EDA section that 80% of the respondents to this questions fell in the 1-3 drinks categories, and another 10% fell in the 4-6 drinks categories. As a reminder, below we can see the table of counts by group of number of drinks consumed per day. We can see that there are many more people per group in the fewer number of drinks per day categories than in the greater number of drinks per day categories. We cannot be certain that this difference in numbers is solely responsible for the low p_value, but it is important to keep in mind when interpreting this analysis.

Diabetes & Depression Analysis

For the diabetes and depression analysis, we selected four columns that we felt summarised many of the symptoms experienced by someone with depression: little interest in doing things, feeling down, depressed, or hopeless, feeling bad about yourself, and poor appetite or overeating. We want to acknowledge that, of course, these are not the only things that people with depression experience. Depression is a very dynamic and complicated condition that everyone experiences differently. We are unable to explore every aspect of it, so for the sake of our analysis, we chose a few variables that we thought were representative.

Little Interest in Doing Things

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Little Interest in Doing Things: More than half the days -0.1526861 0.1269116 -1.203091 0.2289412
Little Interest in Doing Things: Not at all -0.1406082 0.1402051 -1.002875 0.3159209
Little Interest in Doing Things: Several days NA NA NA NA

There didn’t seem to be any significant different in age informed of diabetes between groups who did not experience decreased interest in doing things, and those who did.

Feeling Down, Depressed, or Hopeless

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Feeling Down, Depressed, or Hopeless: Not at all 0.30153062 0.1432669 2.1046772 0.03531941
Feeling Down, Depressed, or Hopeless: Several days 0.05599828 0.1356369 0.4128542 0.67971343

Again, there didn’t seem to be any significant different in age informed of diabetes between groups who did not feel down, depressed, or hopeless, and those who did.

Feeling Bad About Yourself

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Feeling Bad About Yourself: More than half the days 0.05956465 0.1802531 0.3304502 0.7410598
Feeling Bad About Yourself: Not at all 0.18729251 0.1631326 1.1480997 0.2509274
Feeling Bad About Yourself: Several days NA NA NA NA

We encountered similar results in the feeling bad about yourself category and didn’t seem to be any significant different in age informed of diabetes between groups who did not experience negative perception of themselves, and those who did.

Poor Appetite or Overeating

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Poor Appetite or Overeating: Several days -0.01626986 0.1274829 -0.1276239 0.8984466
Poor Appetite or Overeating: More than half the days 0.02857535 0.1428528 0.2000335 0.8414544

None of the depression markers seem to have a statistically significant impact on age informed of diabetes, indicating that there is not sufficient evidence to say that people with diabetes experience depression differently that people without diabetes. For all of these questions, but particularly to the depression related questions, it is important to consider that this data was gathered through a survey and is susceptible to response bias. For many individuals, depression is a sensitive topic that they may be hesitant to report or be honest about in a survey due to social and internalized stigma. There were only between 300-400 responses per question, which only a small fraction of the data set and respondents, and therefore is likely the reason that this analysis does not find statistical significance between type II diabetes and depression when much of the literature does.

Health Access and Hospital Use & Diabetes

For the health access and hospital use analysis, we selected only one variable: general health condition. Many of the other variables were quite specific and didn’t encompass a large amount of the data set and they related to specific hospital usage, so we felt that this variable encompassed the best overview of someone’s health access and condition.

General Health Condition

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
General Health Condition: Fair -0.4314874 0.2053868 -2.100853 0.0356538937
General Health Condition: Good -0.5294216 0.2047880 -2.585217 0.0097317642
General Health Condition: Poor -0.4611580 0.2154663 -2.140279 0.0323322537
General Health Condition: Very Good -0.7085673 0.2141103 -3.309356 0.0009351095

We do see a statistically significant difference in age informed of diabetes between health groups. Those who reported excellent health conditions tended to be informed earlier than those who reported any of the other health conditions. We are curious that those who reported excellent health condition tended to be informed first relative to the other and those who reported very good health conditions tended to be informed later than the other groups.

Insurance and Diabetes Data

For the insurance data set, we chose the general insurance coverage question. We felt like knowing whether or not someone was covered by insurance was enough to assess their insurance situation. The rest of the variables asked what type of insurance they had, with almost 10 different insurance options to choose from, and we felt like those did not carry as much information.

Insurance Coverage

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Covered by Health Insurance: No 0.5079257 0.09242908 5.495302 3.900431e-08

There is a statistically significant difference in the age informed of diabetes between individuals who are and are not covered by health insurance. Those who are not covered by health insurance tend to be informed of diabetes earlier than those who are covered by health insurance. This may be due to the most consistent health visits that people covered by health insurance have as health care may not be as inaccessible and expensive for them. Individuals with health insurance may catch signs of diabetes earlier and can take the appropriate actions to prevent acceleration or worsening conditions of diabetes.

Occupation Data

Finally, for the occupation analysis, we selected type of job, which more indicates job status than type of work, as well as hours worked the previous week. We felt that these two variables adequately represented someone’s work status.

Type of Job

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Type of Work Done Last Week: With a job or business but not at work 0.1914783 0.22365870 0.8561181 3.919325e-01
Type of Work Done Last Week: Not working at a job or business -0.5785971 0.05922006 -9.7702891 1.510205e-22
Type of Work Done Last Week: Looking for work 0.1041882 0.19480443 0.5348346 5.927642e-01

There is a statistically significant difference between work status and age informed of diabetes. It seems that those who are looking for work tending to be informed earlier in life and at about 40-50 years old, there is a switch to people who are with a job or business but not at work being informed earlier.

Hours Worked

term estimate std.error statistic p.value
Hours Worked Last Week All Jobs 0.01094949 0.003195085 3.426978 0.0006103376

There is also statistically significant difference in age informed of diabetes in both groups with different work status and in groups with a different number of work hours. Earlier in life, those who work 21-30 hours tended to be informed earlier, and at around age 40, more people who worked 61-70 hours started being informed. We see a huge drop in ‘survival probability’ for this group around 40 years.
